  try(
    data(
      "deboeck2015phi",
      package = "cTMed"
    ),
    silent = TRUE
  )
}
```

## Using Results from the dynr Package

```{r}
phi <- deboeck2015phi$dynr$phi
vcov_phi_vec <- deboeck2015phi$dynr$vcov
phi
vcov_phi_vec
```

> **Note:** The input argument `phi` matrix is required to have column and rownames
> as they are used to trace the path of the independent variable column (`from = "x"`)
> to the dependent variable row (`to = "y"`) through mediator variables (`med = "m"`).
> The argument `vcov_phi_vec` does not require names.

### Plot the Effects as a Function of the Time-Interval

```{r dynr-med}
med <- Med(
  phi = phi,
  delta_t = seq(from = 0, to = 20, length.out = 1000),
  from = "x",
  to = "y",
  med = "m"
)
plot(med)
```

### Monte Carlo Method for Total, Direct, and Indirect Effects for a Range of Time-Intervals

The Monte Carlo method confidence intervals of the total, direct, and indirect effects
from $X$ to $Y$ through $M$ at a range of time-intervals (0 to 20) is calculated using the `DeltaMed()` function.
If the length of `delta_t` is long or number of replications `R` is large,
using multiple cores by specifying the number of cores to use `ncores` can make the calculations run faster.

```{r dynr-mc}
mc <- MCMed(
  phi = phi,
  vcov_phi_vec = vcov_phi_vec,
  delta_t = seq(from = 0, to = 20, length.out = 1000),
  from = "x",
  to = "y",
  med = "m",
  R = 1000L,
  ncores = parallel::detectCores(),
  seed = 42
)
plot(mc)
```

```{r}
#| include = FALSE
file <- root$find_file(
  ".setup",
  "data-raw",
  "mc.Rds"
)
saveRDS(mc, file = file, compress = "xz")
```

Notice that the lower and upper bounds of the confidence intervals can be asymmetric around the estimate.

```{r ctsem-mc-2}
#| echo = FALSE
mc <- MCMed(
  phi = phi,
  vcov_phi_vec = vcov_phi_vec,
  delta_t = seq(from = 15, to = 20, length.out = 1000),
  from = "x",
  to = "y",
  med = "m",
  R = 1000L,
  ncores = parallel::detectCores(),
  seed = 42
)
plot(mc)
```

## Using Results from the ctsem Package

`phi` in the case of the `ctsem` results is the mean of the posterior distribution of the drift matrix
and `vcov_phi_vec` is the corresponding covariance matrix.

```{r}
phi <- deboeck2015phi$ctsem$phi
vcov_phi_vec <- deboeck2015phi$ctsem$vcov
posterior_phi <- deboeck2015phi$ctsem$posterior_phi
phi
vcov_phi_vec
```

### Plot the Effects as a Function of the Time-Interval

```{r ctsem-med}
med <- Med(
  phi = phi,
  delta_t = seq(from = 0, to = 20, length.out = 1000),
  from = "x",
  to = "y",
  med = "m"
)
plot(med)
```

### Monte Carlo Method for Total, Direct, and Indirect Effects for a Range of Time-Intervals

```{r ctsem-mc}
mc <- MCMed(
  phi = phi,
  vcov_phi_vec = vcov_phi_vec,
  delta_t = seq(from = 0, to = 20, length.out = 1000),
  from = "x",
  to = "y",
  med = "m",
  R = 1000L,
  ncores = parallel::detectCores(),
  seed = 42
)
plot(mc)
```

### Credible Intervals for the Total, Direct, and Indirect Effects Using the Posterior Distribution of the Drift Matrix

```{r ctsem-posterior}
posterior <- PosteriorMed(
  phi = posterior_phi,
  delta_t = seq(from = 0, to = 20, length.out = 1000),
  from = "x",
  to = "y",
  med = "m",
  ncores = parallel::detectCores()
)
plot(posterior)
```

```{r}
#| include = FALSE
file <- root$find_file(
  ".setup",
  "data-raw",
  "posterior.Rds"
)
saveRDS(posterior, file = file, compress = "xz")
```

Notice that the lower and upper bounds of the credible intervals can be asymmetric around the posterior mean.

```{r ctsem-posterior-2}
#| echo = FALSE
posterior <- PosteriorMed(
  phi = posterior_phi,
  delta_t = seq(from = 15, to = 20, length.out = 1000),
  from = "x",
  to = "y",
  med = "m",
  ncores = parallel::detectCores()
)
plot(posterior)
```

